Introduction

Method

Participants

A total of sample of N = 46744 participants (22377, female, 24169 male, 139 other, Mage = 43.07, min = 18, max = 100, SD = 16.01), were recruited from 67 countries.

Isolating just the participants in USA and NZL samples, left a total of N = 1980 participants (965, female, 1008 male, 5 other, Mage = 44.7, min = 18, max = 100, SD = 16.76). The USA sample consisted of n = 1471 participants (710, female, 755 male, 4 other, Mage = 44.32, SD = 16.43; and the New Zealand sample consisted of n = 509 participants (255, female, 253 male, 1 other, Mage = 45.78, SD = 17.63.

Results

Testing Differences Between USA and NZL

In the analysis that follows we focus only on the USA and New Zealand samples (N = 1980). We have only reported effects for the variables of interest (Moral Circle, Moral Identity Internalization, Symbolic Moral Identity, Political Ideology, and Country), however the values reported are taken from the full model including relevant covariates, all the full regression tables are reported in the supplementary analysis.

Policy Support

Without Country

First we conducted regression for all variables across the full dataset (without accounting for Country). This model was significant R2 = 0.25, F(17, 1932) = 37.28, p < .001. Of the variables of interest, Moral Circle b = 0.04, 95% CI = [0.00, 0.09], t(1932) = 2.00, p = .045, Internalized Moral Identity , b = 0.24, 95% CI = [0.19, 0.29], t(1932) = 9.54, p = < .001, Symbolic Moral Identity , b = 0.12, 95% CI = [0.07, 0.17], t(1932) = 4.46, p = < .001, and Political Ideology , b = -0.16, 95% CI = [-0.20, -0.11], t(1932) = -7.11, p = < .001, were significant predictors in the model. Furthermore, there was a significant interaction between Political Ideology and both Internalized Moral Identity, b = -0.10, 95% CI = [-0.14, -0.07], t(1932) = -5.80, p < .001, and Symbolic Moral Identity, b = 0.09, 95% CI = [0.06, 0.13], t(1932) = 5.33, p < .001.

With Country

Next we added Country as an interaction term. Again the model was significant R2 = 0.3, F(35, 1914) = 23.67, p < .001. And the model performed significantly better than the previous model F(18, 1914) = 8.38, p < .001.

With the inclusion of Country as an interaction term many of the effects described above were no longer observed, however we did find a significant Country × Political Ideology interaction, b = -0.15, 95% CI = [-0.25, -0.05], t(1914) = -2.89, p = .004.

Most importantly, we found a significant three way Country × Internalized Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction, b = -0.13, 95% CI = [-0.22, -0.03], t(1914) = -2.69, p = .007; this was not observed for Symbolization b = 0.06, 95% CI = [-0.03, 0.15], t(1914) = 1.28, p = .202. To interpret these interactions we conducted regressions for the USA and New Zealand samples separately.

USA Regression

For the USA sample, the overall model significantly predicted Policy Support R2 = 0.29, F(17, 1430) = 34.81, p < .001, with both Internalised Moral Identity, b = 0.25, 95% CI = [0.19, 0.31], t(1430) = 8.28, p = < .001, and Political Ideology, b = -0.17, 95% CI = [-0.22, -0.12], t(1430) = -6.56, p = < .001, significantly predicting Policy Support in the USA sample. Importantly the predicted Internalized Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction was observed b = -0.11, 95% CI = [-0.14, -0.07], t(1430) = -5.46, p = < .001.

We note that in the USA Sample Moral Circle was also a significant predictor b = 0.06, 95% CI = [0.01, 0.11], t(1430) = 2.35, p .019; furthermore we also observed a significant Symbolic Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction, b = 0.10, 95% CI = [0.07, 0.14], t(1430) = 5.47, p < .001.

New Zealand Regression

For the New Zealand sample, the overall model significantly predicted Policy Support R2 = 0.21, F(17, 484) = 7.52, p < .001, and while, the predictive power of the model lay primarily with the covariates, we note that there Internalized Moral Identity, was also a significant predictor of Policy Support in the New Zealand b = 0.19, 95% CI = [0.10, 0.27], t(484) = 4.49, p = < .001.

Political Ideology, b = -0.02, 95% CI = [-0.10, 0.06], t(484) = -0.54, p = .590, was not a significant predictor. There was no significant Internalized Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction observed b = 0.02, 95% CI = [-0.05, 0.10], t(484) = 0.60, p = .550. we note that also that Moral Circle was not a significant predictor b = 0.00, 95% CI = [-0.07, 0.07], t(484) = 0.01, p .991; and we observed no significant Symbolic Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction, b = 0.04, 95% CI = [-0.03, 0.12], t(484) = 1.19, p = .233.

Plot

Figure 1 shows the relationship between Political Ideology and Internal Moral Identity in predicting Policy Support for the New Zealand sample and the USA sample separately.

Figure 1: USA: Interaction between Political Ideology and Internal Moral Identity in predicting Policy Support

Physical Contact

Without Country

As with Policy Support, we conducted regression for all variables across the full dataset (without accounting for Country), and this model was significant R2 = 0.36, F(17, 1932) = 64.68, p < .001. Internalized Moral Identity was a significant predictor in the model b = 0.34, 95% CI = [0.30, 0.39], t(1932) = 14.18, p = < .001; while Political Ideology was not a significant predictor, b = -0.04, 95% CI = [-0.08, 0.00], t(1932) = -1.94, p = .052. We found a significant interaction between Political Ideology and both Internalized Moral Identity, b = -0.04, 95% CI = [-0.08, -0.01], t(1932) = -2.71, p .007, and Symbolic Moral Identity, b = 0.05, 95% CI = [0.02, 0.09], t(1932) = 3.35, p .001. Interestingly we also observed a significant Moral Circle × Internalized Moral Identity Interaction b = 0.05, 95% CI = [0.01, 0.08], t(1932) = 2.44, p = .015.

With Country

When we added Country as an interaction term the model remained significant R2 = 0.42, F(35, 1914) = 38.94, p < .001, and performed significantly better than the previous model F(18, 1914) = 9.68, p < .001.

Internalized Moral Identiy remained a significant predictor in the model b = 0.36, 95% CI = [0.31, 0.42], t(1914) = 13.09, p = < .001; and Political Ideology emerged as a significant predictor, b = -0.05, 95% CI = [-0.09, 0.00], t(1914) = -2.03, p = .043. We found a significant interaction between Political Ideology and both Internalized Moral Identity, b = -0.05, 95% CI = [-0.08, -0.01], t(1914) = -2.67, p .008, and Symbolic Moral Identity, b = 0.07, 95% CI = [0.04, 0.10], t(1914) = 3.98, p < .001. We also found a significant Moral Circle × Symbolic Moral Identity interaction b = 0.04, 95% CI = [0.00, 0.08], t(1914) = 2.10, p = .036.

Regarding interactions with Country, we found a significant Country × Internalized Moral Identity interaction b = -0.12, 95% CI = [-0.22, -0.02], t(1932) = -2.25, p = .025; a significant Country × Symbolic Moral Identity interaction b = -0.17, 95% CI = [-0.28, -0.06], t(1932) = -3.00, p = .003; and a significant Country × Political Ideology interaction, b = 0.11, 95% CI = [0.01, 0.21], t(1932) = 2.25, p = .024.

We also observed a significant three way Country × Internalized Moral Identiy × Political Ideology interaction b = 0.09, 95% CI = [0.00, 0.18], t(1932) = 2.06, p = .039; this was not observed for Symbolization b = -0.06, 95% CI = [-0.14, 0.03], t(1932) = -1.26, p = .209. Again we conducted regressions for the USA and New Zealand samples separately.

USA Regression

For the USA sample, the overall model significantly predicted adherence to Physical Contact measures R2 = 0.4, F(17, 1430) = 55.3, p < .001, with both Internalised Moral Identity, b = 0.36, 95% CI = [0.31, 0.42], t(1430) = 12.66, p = < .001, and Political Ideology, b = -0.05, 95% CI = [-0.10, 0.00], t(1430) = -1.96, p = .050, significantly predicting adherence to Physical Contact measures in the USA sample. Importantly the predicted Internalized Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction was observed b = -0.05, 95% CI = [-0.08, -0.01], t(1430) = -2.59, p = .010.

We note that in the USA we also observed a significant Symbolic Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction b = 0.07, 95% CI = [0.03, 0.10], t(1430) = 3.85, p < .001; and a significant Moral Circle × Symbolic Moral Identity interaction, b = 0.04, 95% CI = [0.00, 0.09], t(1430) = 2.03, p = .043.

New Zealand Regression

For the New Zealand sample, the overall model significantly predicted adherence to Physical Contact measures R2 = 0.32, F(17, 484) = 13.4, p < .001. As with Policy Support, the predictive power of the model lay primarily with the covariates, with Internalized Moral Identity, b = 0.24, 95% CI = [0.16, 0.32], t(484) = 5.96, p = < .001, the only variable of interst that predicted adherence to Physical Contact measures in the New Zealand sample when controlling for the covariates.

Political Ideology, b = 0.06, 95% CI = [-0.01, 0.14], t(484) = 1.64, p = .102, was not a significant predictor, and the Internalized Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction was not observed b = 0.05, 95% CI = [-0.03, 0.12], t(484) = 1.25, p = .213.

We note that also that a significant Symbolic Moral Identity × Political Ideology interaction was not observed b = 0.01, 95% CI = [-0.06, 0.08], t(484) = 0.35, p .726; nor did we find a a significant significant Moral Circle × Symbolic Moral Identity interaction, b = 0.01, 95% CI = [-0.06, 0.08], t(484) = 0.21, p = .831.

Plot

Figure 2 shows the relationship between Political Ideology and Internal Moral Identity in predicting Physical Contact for the New Zealand sample and the USA sample separately.

Figure 2: USA: Interaction between Political Ideology and Internal Moral Identity in predicting Physical Contact

Physical Hygiene

Without Country

In line with the previous analyses, we conducted regression for all variables across the full dataset (without accounting for Country), and this model was significant R2 = 0.27, F(17, 1931) = 41.61, p < .001. Internalized Moral Identity was a significant predictor in the model b = 0.21, 95% CI = [0.16, 0.26], t(1931) = 8.45, p = < .001; as was Symbolic Moral Identity, b = 0.23, 95% CI = [0.18, 0.28], t(1931) = 8.80, p = < .001. We also found a significant interaction between Political Ideology and Internalized Moral Identity, b = -0.05, 95% CI = [-0.09, -0.02], t(1931) = -3.17, p = .002.

With Country

Again we added Country as an interaction term, and the model remained significant R2 = 0.28, F(35, 1913) = 21.76, p < .001, again, the inclusion of Country as an interaction term significantly improved the model F(18, 1913) = 2.47, p < .001.

Internalized Moral Identity was a significant predictor in the model b = 0.23, 95% CI = [0.17, 0.29], t(1913) = 7.84, p = < .001; as was Symbolic Moral Identity, b = 0.21, 95% CI = [0.15, 0.27], t(1913) = 7.14, p = < .001. There was also a significant Political Ideology × Internalized Moral Identity interaction, b = -0.05, 95% CI = [-0.09, -0.02], t(1913) = -2.88, p = .004 remained. There were no additional effects involving the variables of interest. While there was no significant interaction with Country and any of the variables of interest, for consistency, we proceeded with regressions for the USA and New Zealand samples separately.

Predicted three way interactions were not observed for b = -0.05, 95% CI = [-0.14, 0.05], t(1913) = -0.98, p = .327; nor for Symbolization b = -0.03, 95% CI = [-0.13, 0.06], t(1913) = -0.71, p = .476.

USA Regression

For the USA sample, the overall model significantly predicted adherence to Physical Hygiene measures R2 = 0.31, F(17, 1429) = 37.46, p < .001.

Internalized Moral Identity was a significant predictor in the model b = 0.23, 95% CI = [0.17, 0.29], t(1429) = 8.01, p = < .001; as was Symbolic Moral Identity, b = 0.21, 95% CI = [0.16, 0.27], t(1429) = 7.29, p = < .001, and the significant interaction between Political Ideology and Internalized Moral Identity, b = -0.05, 95% CI = [-0.09, -0.02], t(1429) = -2.95, p .003 was also present.

New Zealand Regression

For the New Zealand sample, the overall model was also significant R2 = 0.17, F(17, 484) = 5.93, p < .001

Both Internalized Moral Identity b = 0.13, 95% CI = [0.03, 0.23], t(484) = 2.50, p = .013, and Symbolic Moral Identity were significant predictors in the model, b = 0.22, 95% CI = [0.12, 0.33], t(484) = 4.07, p = < .001. A significant interaction between Political Ideology and Internalized Moral Identity was observed, b = -0.10, 95% CI = [-0.19, -0.01], t(484) = -2.15, p .032.

Plot

Figure 3 shows the relationship between Political Ideology and Internal Moral Identity in predicting Physical Hygiene for the New Zealand sample and the USA sample separately (note that these effects are equivalent).

Figure 3: USA: Interaction between Political Ideology and Internal Moral Identity in predicting Physical Hygiene

Supplementary Analysis

Initial testing revealed that for Policy Support, allowing intercepts to vary with Country significantly improved the predictive power of the model \(\chi\)2(1) = 8290.99, p < .001.

Similarly, for Physical Contact, allowing intercepts to vary with Country significantly improved the predictive power of the model \(\chi\)2(1) = 3951.04, p < .001.

Finally, for Physical Hygiene, allowing intercepts to vary with Country significantly improved the predictive power of the model \(\chi\)2(1) = 4677.74, p < .001. The country level residuals for the full models for each dependent variable are plotted below.
